# API Design Standards

## RESTful Conventions
- Use standard HTTP methods (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE)
- Follow RESTful resource naming conventions
- Use appropriate HTTP status codes

## Authentication & Authorization
- **Authentication**: All endpoints require valid Firebase ID token
- **Server-Side Verification**: All API routes must verify authentication tokens server-side
- **Role-Based Access**: Implement role-based access control using Firebase custom claims
- **Permission Checks**: Verify user permissions before processing requests

## Input Validation
- **Zod Schemas**: All API inputs must be validated with Zod schemas
- **Type Safety**: Use TypeScript types for all request/response structures
- **Error Messages**: Return clear, actionable validation error messages

## Error Handling
- **Consistent Format**: Use consistent error response format across all endpoints
- **Error Codes**: Use appropriate HTTP status codes
- **Error Messages**: User-friendly error messages, no technical details exposed
- **Sanitization**: Sanitize errors before logging (no PII, stack traces in production)

## Rate Limiting
- **Default Limits**: 20 requests/minute, 100/hour, 500/day
- **Admin Exemption**: Admins are exempt from rate limiting
- **Rate Limit Headers**: Include rate limit information in response headers
- **Error Responses**: Return 429 Too Many Requests when rate limit exceeded

## Response Format
- **JSON Structure**: Consistent JSON response structure across all endpoints
- **Success Responses**: Include relevant data and metadata
- **Error Responses**: Include error code, message, and optional details
- **Status Codes**: Use appropriate HTTP status codes

## CORS
- **Restrict Origins**: Restrict to specific origins (no wildcards in production)
- **Environment Variables**: Use `ALLOWED_ORIGINS` environment variable
- **Headers**: Include appropriate CORS headers in responses

## API Documentation
- **Endpoint Documentation**: Document all API endpoints with:
  - HTTP method and path
  - Request parameters (query, body, headers)
  - Response format and status codes
  - Authentication requirements
  - Rate limiting information
  - Example requests and responses
- **Error Responses**: Document all possible error responses and status codes
- **Versioning**: Document API versioning strategy

## Security
- **Input Sanitization**: Sanitize all user inputs
- **SQL Injection Prevention**: Use parameterized queries (Firestore handles this)
- **XSS Prevention**: Sanitize output data
- **CSRF Protection**: Implement CSRF protection where applicable
- **PII Protection**: Never log or expose PII in error messages or logs
